
# Generate Geo Map using Google Sheets Data

This tutorial is to plot map using Google Sheets data.

Then, we are going to create a marker for each geo-point. 

With each 

**Reference**

- https://community.plotly.com/t/adding-images-to-annotations/1326
- Article on how to import data from Gogole Sheets to Collab - https://medium.com/analytics-vidhya/colab-and-google-sheets-surprisingly-powerful-combination-for-data-science-part-1-bbbb11cbd8e


# Phase 1: Data Preparation

## Step 1: Set Up Authentication to Google Account

Once you run the code chunk below, it'll generate a link. Follow the link, it may ask you to sign in to your Google Account, make sure you select the account where the Google Sheets is being stored. 

![Screenshot 2021-07-23 at 2.32.51 PM.png](data:image/png;base64,)


Copy the code, paste it in the box in the kernel.

Then, press Enter on the keyboard. This will authenticate you and will allow you to interact with Google Sheets and other Google apps in your notebook.


```python
from google.colab import auth
auth.authenticate_user()

import gspread
from oauth2client.client import GoogleCredentials
gc = gspread.authorize(GoogleCredentials.get_application_default())
```

## Step 2: Get Google Sheets Data 

1. We can open the google sheets and retrieve the data by using `open_by_url` function.

2. To get the table by the tab names, we can use `worksheet` function. The data returned would be in matrix format.


```python
sheet = gc.open_by_url('https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1MtbcFYYVgA7i6evF8RPpl9u9KLhQyZHW07-dZvdnCp4/edit#gid=0')
tab = sheet.worksheet('data')
```


```python
data = tab.get_all_values()
```

## Step 3: Reformat Matrix to Pandas Dataframe

To improve the readability, we are going to convert the matrix data to DataFrame.


```python
import pandas as pd
df_raw = pd.DataFrame(data)

df_raw.head()
```

## Step 4: Extract Geo-Point From URL Link


```python
url_list = df['Google API Link'].str.extract('[a-zA-Z://.+@]+(.*,)', expand=False)
lat_list = url_list.str.extract('([0-9. ]+),').astype(float)
long_list = url_list.str.extract(',([0-9. ]+),').astype(float)


```


```python
# append list as new column
df.insert(10, "geo_lat", lat_list) 
df.insert(11, "geo_long", long_list) 
# df['geo_lat'] = lat_list 
# df['geo_long'] = long_list
```

The next step is to read mapbox token which I stored in a separate file in Google Drive.


```python
from google.colab import drive
```

```python
#customize using update_layout()
import plotly.graph_objects as go


fig = px.scatter_mapbox(df, lat="geo_lat", lon="geo_long", color="Shop Name",zoom=8,hover_name="Shop Name", hover_data=["Branch", "Address"])

fig = go.Figure(go.Scattermapbox(
    mode = "markers+text",
     marker=go.scattermapbox.Marker(
            size=14, symbol="shop",color="blue"
        ),
    text = df["Shop Name"],
    lat=df['geo_lat'],
    lon=df['geo_long'],
    hovertemplate =
    "<b>%{text}</b><br><br>" +
    "Name: %{text}<br>"
    ))


fig.update_layout(
    hovermode = 'closest',
    mapbox = dict(
        accesstoken=my_token,
        bearing=0,
        center=go.layout.mapbox.Center(
            lat=3,
            lon=100
        ),
        pitch=0,
        zoom=5
    )
)

fig.show()
```
